<p class="p">Similarly, the analytical framework proposed by [
 <xref rid="pone.0219393.ref018" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">18</xref>], [
 <xref rid="pone.0219393.ref017" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">17</xref>] and [
 <xref rid="pone.0219393.ref019" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">19</xref>] suggest absorptive, adaptive and transformative capacities as the three core components of resilience deem to sound for resilience analysis. In this sense, the FAO’s Resilience Index Measurement and Analysis (RIMA) indicators [
 <xref rid="pone.0219393.ref036" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">36</xref>] were aggregated by equal weighting approach and subsumed into the three resilience components to capture households’ resilience to climate change-induced shocks [
 <xref rid="pone.0219393.ref012" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">12</xref>,
 <xref rid="pone.0219393.ref017" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">17</xref>,
 <xref rid="pone.0219393.ref018" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">18</xref>,
 <xref rid="pone.0219393.ref020" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">20</xref>]. Where resilience is the function of the three core components expressed as: 
